  <span id="freeText3205057477042038226" style="display:none"><blockquote>That we are capable only of being what we are remains our unforgivable sin.</blockquote><br /><br />RIP Gene Wolfe, 1931 - 2019. On hearing news of his death earlier this month, I felt inspired to pick up his masterpiece again, even though it had been less than half a year since I read it the first time.<br /><br />I can now confirm what Neil Gaiman and everyone else in the know says about the late Mr Wolfe: his books yield greater mysteries and wonders on being reread. <br /><br />Book of the New Sun has one of the most haunting openings in literature. The first 80 or so pages - up to Thecla's {spoiler} - are an astonishing tour de force. I don't know of anything else like it. After that, things can get rather bewildering. Subplots pile on subplots, and it's not always clear if Severian's adventures are happening in the same world at all. A second time through, this was all much easier to navigate. Being already somewhat familiar with Urth, I was able to to catch internal consistencies I'd missed before... Much is still obscure, it hardly needs to be said.<br /><br />...<br /><br />The book begins in a moral abyss, and Severian's act of mercy, however audacious, remains equivocal. He acts more from a momentary lapse of discipline than anything like a moral conversion. Afterwards he continues perpetrating hideous evil with hardly a second thought. Is he a savior figure, or is it rather that the possibility of grace may enter even the most twisted and hopeless sinner in moments of weakness? <br /><br />The whole book, from prose to characters and all the things described, aches with a longing for salvation. This too is more apparent on a second reading. To take but one example, I barely noticed Master Gurloes the first time; on this reading he started to seem like a major character, at once horrifying and terribly poignant. He understands more than most, possibly more than Severian himself. <br /><br />The salvation at hand is highly ambiguous. For those doomed to experience it, it likely won't be distinguishable from total destruction. Salvation maybe, but for who?<br /><br />If you've read any of the obituaries, you're probably aware that Wolfe was a devout Catholic. Happily, this does not mean Aslan the lion. This is much more a Good Friday than an Easter book. Even better, a book of symbols rather than allegory<br /><br /><blockquote>We believe that we invent symbols. The truth is that they invent us; we are their creatures, shaped by their hard, defining edges. </blockquote><br /><br />Prous, Faulkner, the Church Fathers, Conan the Barbarian. Philosophy, art, pulp are fused in an impossibly seamless whole. Religious, yes, but never reductive. The scene in Claw of the Conciliator (#2) where he eats the corpse of his beloved a month or so after her death is one of the most beautiful depictions of love I know in literature.<br /><br /> <blockquote>At one instant we walked mutely together in what surely must have been the paradise the New Sun is said to open to all who, in their final moments, call upon him; and though the wise teach that it is closed to those who are their own executioners, yet I cannot but think that he who forgives so much must sometimes forgive that as well. </blockquote><br /><br /><br />*************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************<br /><br /><blockquote>Somewhere among the swirling worlds I am so soon to explore, there lives a race like and yet unlike the human. They are no taller than we. Their bodies are like ours save they are perfect, and that the standard to which they adhere is wholly alien to us. Like us, they have eyes, a nose, a mouth; but they use these features (which are, as I have said, perfect) to express emotions we have never felt , so that for us to see their faces is to look upon some ancient and terrible alphabet of feeling, at once supremely important and utterly unintelligible. </blockquote><br /><br />Beautiful, haunting, strange. <br /><br />This is just the first of two volumes, but I'd say the series is in the running to match or exceed Perdido Street Station as my personal favorite work of sci fi/fantasy. The New Sun is a significantly more arduous read than Mieville's great book. Wolfe writes like Proust or Faulkner. I've stopped periodically throughout to go back and read a chapter a second time. <br /><br />Often difficult to follow the logic by which certain genre classics break into the mainstream - or postmodern - literary canon. A lot of pulp actually does just kind of suck (*cough*<i>Neuromancer</i>), but in this one case I have to say, Believe the hype.</span>
